Sed, the stream editor.

Sed reads its input line by line, applies a little editing script to each line, and writes the result to standard output. The good news is that the overwhelming majority of real-world sed use is a single command: substitution, written s, slash, the pattern, slash, the replacement, slash. Learn just that and you have covered almost everything you will ever need.

By default, substitution replaces only the first match on each line. Add the g flag, for global, at the end and it replaces every match on the line. Add an i flag and the match becomes case-insensitive. As with grep, use the dash capital-e flag for extended regular expressions, so you do not have to escape the plus, question mark, parentheses, and braces.

Sed has one feature worth singling out: back-references. When you wrap part of your pattern in parentheses, you capture it, and you can refer back to those captured pieces in the replacement as backslash-one, backslash-two, and so on, counting the parentheses from the left. That is how you reorder or restructure text, for instance swapping two words around.

Two more practical points. You can choose a different delimiter when your pattern itself contains slashes, which gets ugly with file paths; just use a vertical bar or a hash sign instead of the slash, and it reads far more cleanly. And the dash i flag edits a file in place, changing it directly instead of printing to the screen, optionally keeping a backup copy. When sed starts to feel clunky, with multiple substitutions or anything that needs to remember state, that is your signal to reach for awk or a real scripting language. Keep sed for what it does beautifully: simple substitutions inside a pipeline.
